                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-158-off841 t18280221-158-victim974"></join>
                  </persName>
            , his master.</p>
               <p>GEORGE ROGERS. I am a <rs id="t18280221-158-viclabel843" type="occupation">tobacconist</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-158-victim974 t18280221-158-viclabel843"></join>, and live in St. Giles's. The prisoner was in my employ; it was a part of his duty to deliver goods - he had 42 lbs. of tobacco, and 17 lbs. of snuff to deliver to customers at Kensington, and other places - he went away, and I heard no more of him for three weeks - on the day after Christmas, I received this letter, which is his writing: -</p>
               <p>"SIR, December 26th, 1827.</p>
               <p>I write this to inform you, that I met with a young man on Monday last, when I was going to deliver your goods; I had unfortunately drank rather too freely, and was not aware of the time being so late, I sat down to take rest and fell asleep; when I awoke, my bag was gone, and I did not like to return; but I hope you will forgive, GEORGE ROOTSEY."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-158-person975">
                  JOHN 
                  MERIDITH
               <interp inst="t18280221-158-person975" type="surname" value="MERIDITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-158-person975" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-158-person975" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to the prosecutor. I sent the prisoner out with several parcels, in a bag, to deliver to different persons.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I got into a public-house, at Knights-bridge, and was afraid to return home.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280221-158-verdict844" type="verdictDescription">
